bio:
Not sure what to write here.
It’s seems every time I define myself I confine myself.
Here are bits and pieces of my journey.

social_posts.post_text: the more you care about how you feel, the less you’ll care about the way you are perceived.. and the greater the impact you will have on others. self care comes in so many different forms. self love can look self hating to other people. if you want happiness you have to listen to your intuition. listen to the voice that is saying im lonely! or my body is tired! or I want to express myself! you have to ask yourself every day throughout the day “what would someone who loves themselves do?” until treating yourself with love and care becomes the new normal. you deserve the love you desire even if you’ve never received it. take small steps to become that person for yourself and watch the world around you transform before your eyes and turn into heaven on earth

Back in Baltimore four years later! Thank you to every person who approached me to share kind and loving words. I feel incredibly loved, appreciated, and seen.. and definitely cried like a baby on my way home 🥲
Mood when I hear a new Kranium song 😭

I dance to connect with myself. I often meet people who think they’re too stiff and cannot dance. If you can relate to this, it may be because you’re fearful of being criticized and judged. When creating art let your intention be to connect with yourself, to explore. When you have a purpose and a mission, other people’s opinions of you become less important. Become gentle and curious towards yourself. And see how you start to bloom. I love you 🤍

I used to look at popular girls and imagine what it would be like to be them. It seemed like everything was just so effortless and easy and attainable for them. It felt like everything they had was out of reach for me being stuck with my face and body. Others often laughed at my outfits, said my face looked like someone flicked shit at me, made fun of my “flat” chest, and referred to me by racial slurs. I experienced a lot of bizzare things when I reflect on my childhood. Being able to analyze these experiences and form my own perspective of my appearance has been interesting. Everyone sees me differently. Which makes sense because there’s so many ways to look at me. And sometimes the way people perceive me won’t have anything to do with me at all. I’m not my thoughts or beliefs or anyone else’s whether positive or negative.
I just am. Free.

Music expands my mind and often gives me the feeling I’m time traveling.. It’s so cool there are people who enjoy watching me during these moments and even want to see it in person. Maybe I’ll host something like that one day. Thanks for the love. It touches my heart. My dancing, these videos, are small pieces of me.. Before posting I usually watch each video a hundred times, picking everything apart. I’m going to be doing that less. More sharing.

Made something I saw in my mind. Photo and edit by me. Dress without spots by @eldiorsodeckdesign 🤍

I usually spend a lot more time on fine details but something about the contrasting lines and textures makes my brain feel so good.

I disappear from the world because it often mirrors harmful beliefs I have about myself. Recently I became aware of a deep-seated belief I’ve had that I don’t even deserve to exist, which makes sense considering the childhood/programming I experienced. I disappear from the world for many reasons including debilitating shame from unintentionally hurting many people by doing things I believed were right at the time. Knowing I can hurt others without intending to makes me hesitant to BE at all. For the past years, it’s been this pattern of doing grueling healing work until I feel healed enough to go out into the world and spread love, realizing I have another mountain of healing work to do, and then disappearing again. There’s this component that I’ve been looking at.. shame and isolation. I’ve been training myself to look at myself with new eyes. Eyes of curiosity. In private I ceaselessly berate myself when I see I’ve hurt someone. Because on a subconscious level, I’m trying so damn hard to be nothing like those who hurt me. But what I’m realizing now is that simply having the desire to do better separates me from them. So with this realization I’m choosing to embrace myself. All the messiness. Having good intentions. And continuing to do better. 

It has also evolved into having more compassion, love, and understanding that people can have good intentions and hurt others. And I’ve become mindful of people who add to the cruelty in this world and choose not to introspect or do better even when people in their life are expressing deep hurt. (huge red flag I used to ignore)

I love you world. And I’m learning.

Cacao Ceremony + Guided Womb Meditation + Dance Session 

Sunday, November 19 at 6-8pm
Location : Jersey City near Grove Street PATH Station (exact address provided after RSVP)
Cost : $30

It is my intention to assist you in the removal of blockages, trauma, and programming in the way of your creative expression. Discern the difference between your ultimate purpose and the stories that are injected into your mind by society and/or the media. My mission is to create an inclusive and nurturing environment, where every woman feels a sense of belonging and sisterhood.

We will begin with a cacao ceremony and guided womb healing meditation. Cacao ceremonies offer an opportunity for deep healing, introspection, goal setting, self-love, and transformation. When drinking cacao you may feel yourself dropping into your heart, receiving inspiration, or being in a place of reflection, healing, or forgiveness. Different feelings, emotions, and insights are likely to surface as you are guided through the ceremony and meditation; all are welcome. 

We will then stretch, have a follow along dance session, and group dance circle to explore + express + release. 

Come through and throw that ass in a healing circle! Bring a friend or come alone and make friends! 

ONLY 15 SPOTS AVAILABLE
